{"title_page": "2020 World Figure Skating Championships", "text_new": "{{Infobox Figure Skating Competition\n|title= 2020 World Figure Skating Championships\n|image= 2020_World_Figure_Skating_Championships_logo.png\n|imagesize= \n|caption= \n|comptype= [[ISU Figure Skating Championships|ISU Championship]]\n|startdate= March 16\n|enddate= 22\n|skatingseason= [[2019\u201320 figure skating season|2019\u201320]]\n|location= [[Montreal]], [[Canada]]\n|host= [[Skate Canada]]\n|venue= [[Bell Centre]]\n|prizemoney= \n|defendmen= {{flagicon|USA}} [[Nathan Chen]]\n|defendladies= {{flagicon|RUS}} [[Alina Zagitova]]\n|defendpairs= {{flagicon|CHN}} [[Sui Wenjing]] / [[Han Cong]]\n|defenddance= {{flagicon|FRA}} [[Gabriella Papadakis]] / [[Guillaume Cizeron]]\n|previouscomp= [[2019 World Figure Skating Championships|2019 World Championships]]\n|nextcomp= [[2021 World Figure Skating Championships|2021 World Championships]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 [[World Figure Skating Championships]]''' were scheduled to be held in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], [[Canada]], from March 16\u201322, 2020.<ref name=announcement/> Figure skaters would have competed for the title of world champion in [[Single skating|men's singles, ladies' singles]], [[Pair skating|pairs]], and [[ice dance]]. This would have been the first time that Montreal hosted the World Figure Skating Championships since [[1932 World Figure Skating Championships|1932]].<ref name=host/> The competition was supposed to determine the entry quotas for each federation at the [[2021 World Figure Skating Championships|2021 World Championships]].\n\nThe competition was cancelled on March 11 over concern about the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]], with the possibility of being held later in the year, but not within the current season.<ref name=CBC-031120/><ref name=ISU-031120/> It was the second time the event had been cancelled for reasons other than a World War, after the 1961 World Championships were cancelled following the [[Sabena Flight 548]] crash.<ref name=NBC-031120>{{cite web|url=https://olympics.nbcsports.com/2020/03/11/figure-skating-world-championships-cancellation-nathan-chen/|title=Nathan Chen, skating coaches react to cancellation of world figure skating championships|first=Philip|last=Hersh|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe competition was formally canceled on April 16, after rescheduling was considered.<ref name=canc>{{cite web | URL = https://www.isu.org/isu-news/news/145-news/13139-isu-statement-definite-cancellation-of-pending-2020-isu-championships?templateParam=15 | title = ISU Statement - Definite Cancelation of spending 2020 ISU Championships | date = April 16, 2020 | publisher = ISU}}</ref>\n\n== Reactions to 2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak ==\nAfter a spike in [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] cases from the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] and the cancellation of the [[2020 Women's Ice Hockey World Championships]] in [[Nova Scotia]] by the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]], the [[International Skating Union]] was placed under intense pressure to make a public statement on the status of the 2020 World Figure Skating Championships, as the disease rapidly intensified across the world. The ISU had implemented prevention methods at its events since February 4, 2020 and required all attendees seeking accreditation to complete a questionnaire and temperature check.<ref name=ISU-030220>{{cite web|url=https://isu.org/isu-news/news/145-news/13065-isu-statement-coronavirus-isu-events-season-2019-20?templateParam=15|title=ISU Statement \u2013 Coronavirus \u2013 ISU Events season 2019/20|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Skate Canada]], the host federation, issued a statement on Friday, March 6, that all athletes will be screened for symptoms at the border, undergo health checks, and be required to fill out questionnaires throughout the competition.<ref name=CBC-030920>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/major-events-cancelled-coronavirus-montreal-covid-19-1.5490516|title=Here's how major events in Montreal are handling COVID-19 concerns|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> On Tuesday, March 10, media, officials, skaters, and coaches scheduled to attend the event received a lengthy Coronavirus Information Package from the ISU. All individuals attending the event will be required to undergo a temperature check upon arrival to the competition and must check-in under {{Convert|38|C|F|abbr=}}.<ref name=GN-031020>{{cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6655304/montreal-figure-skating-championships-coronavirus/|title=ISU clamps down on access to world figure skating championships in Montreal amid COVID-19 concerns|first=Lori|last=Ewing|publisher=[[Global News]]|date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Health and Social Services (Quebec)|Quebec Health Ministry]] held a press conference the same day to discuss \"all major events in the province...with input from the [[Public Health Agency of Canada]].\"<ref name=GN-031020/> At the meeting, Quebec Minister of Health [[Danielle McCann]] indicated that cancellation was a possibility, but a final decision had not yet been reached, despite athletes being scheduled to arrive within the next few days.<ref name=GN-031020/>\n\nAt 3:30 PM EDT on Wednesday, March 11, the Quebec government and Quebec Health Ministry made the decision to cancel the World Championships.<ref name=CBC-031120>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/olympics/winter/figureskating/canada-figure-skating-world-championships-1.5493642|title=World figure skating championships cancelled in Montreal|publisher=[[CBC News]]|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> The ISU posted a statement agreeing with the decision, saying that the event could possibly be rescheduled for later in the year, but not before October 2020.<ref name=ISU-031120>{{cite web|url=https://www.isu.org/isu-news/news/145-news/13099-isu-statement-isu-world-figure-skating-championships-2020-montreal?templateParam=15|title=ISU Statement \u2013 ISU World Figure Skating Championships 2020, Montreal|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> It was unclear how the cancellation would affect the [[2020\u201321 figure skating season|upcoming season]] and its subsequent [[2020\u201321 ISU Grand Prix of Figure Skating|Grand Prix]] assignments, which will begin before then.\n\nOn April 12, 2020, ISU Vice-President for Figure Skating, Alexander Lakernik, told media that the chances of rescheduling the championship were slim, due to the ongoing pandemic.<ref name=RGRU-041220>{{cite web|url=https://rg.ru/2020/04/12/lakernik-iz-za-pandemii-shansov-na-provedenie-chempionata-mira-2020-malo.html|title=\u041b\u0435\u0434 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u0442 \u0438 \u0434\u043e\u0436\u0434\u0435\u0442\u0441\u044f|trans-title=The ice will wait and wait|language=Russian|first=Nikolai|last=Dolgopolov|date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The ISU confirmed a complete cancellation of the event, with no chance of postponement to a later date, on April 16.<ref name=ISU-041620>{{cite web|url=https://www.isu.org/isu-news/news/145-news/13139-isu-statement-definite-cancellation-of-pending-2020-isu-championships?templateParam=15|title=ISU Statement \u2013 Definite cancellation of pending 2020 ISU Championships|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=April 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ISU member nations' response ===\nPrior to the cancellation announcement on March 11, the Polish Figure Skating Association asked its athletes on March 10 to make personal decisions by the next day, March 11, on whether or not to attend the event, following the [[Ministry of Sport and Tourism (Poland)|Polish Minister of Sport]]'s recommendation to avoid travel to foreign events.<ref name=PFSA-031020>{{cite web|url=http://www.pfsa.com.pl/index.php|title=Wa\u017cna informacja dotycz\u0105ca koronowirusa|trans-title=Important information about coronavirus|language=Polish|first=Jacek|last=Tascher|author-link=Jacek Tascher|publisher=Polish Figure Skating Association|date=March 10, 2020|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200311070455/http://www.pfsa.com.pl/index.php|archive-date=March 11, 2020|url-status=live|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Skate Canada]], the host federation, postponed several conference calls with its skaters from March 11 to March 13, while awaiting a decision by the local Quebec government on the status of the event.<ref name=SC-031120>{{cite tweet|number=1237741612937162753|user=Ewingsports|title=Quebec Premier (my prvs tweet said health minister) says decision to be announced today on next week's world figure skating championships in Montreal.|first=Lori|last=Ewing|date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral prominent skaters, including two-time reigning men's World Champion [[Nathan Chen]], and coaches [[Rafael Arutyunyan]], [[Lee Barkell]], [[Marie-France Dubreuil]], and [[Brian Orser]], expressed concerns over the possibility of rescheduling the competition to fall 2020, citing the disruption to their training schedules and the proximity to the 2021 edition of the event.<ref name=NBC-031120/>\n\n== Qualification ==\n===Age and minimum TES requirements===\nSkaters are eligible for the 2020 World Championships if they turned 15 years of age before July 1, 2019 and have met the minimum technical elements score requirements. The ISU accepts scores if they were obtained at senior-level ISU-recognized international competitions at least 21 days before the first official practice day of the championships.<ref name=announcement/> The ISU raised the minimum for ladies' singles in both segments on January 8, 2020.<ref name=TES-ladies/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=3 align=center | Minimum technical scores (TES)\n|- bgcolor=b0c4de align=center\n! Discipline\n! [[Short program (figure skating)|SP]] / [[Rhythm dance|RD]]\n! [[Free skating|FS]] / [[Free dance (ice dance)|FD]]\n|-\n! Men || 34 || 64\n|-\n! Ladies || 30 || 51\n|-\n! Pairs || 27 || 44\n|-\n! Ice dance || 33 || 47\n|-\n| colspan=3 align=center | <small> Must be achieved at an ISU-recognized international event<br>in the ongoing or preceding season. <br> SP/RD and FS/FD scores may be attained at different events. </small>\n|}\n\n=== Number of entries per discipline ===\nBased on the results of the [[2019 World Figure Skating Championships|2019 World Championships]], each ISU member nation can field one to three entries per discipline.<ref name=n_entries/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Spots\n! Men\n! Ladies\n! Pairs\n! Dance\n|-\n! 3\n| valign=\"top\" | {{USA}} <br> {{JPN}} <br> \n| valign=\"top\" | {{RUS}} <br> {{KAZ}} <br> {{JPN}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{CHN}} <br> {{RUS}}\n| valign=\"top\" | {{RUS}} <br> {{USA}} <br> {{CAN}}\n|-\n! 2\n| valign=\"top\" |{{CHN}} <br> {{RUS}} <br> {{ITA}} <br> {{CZE}} <br>\n| valign=\"top\" |{{USA}} <br> {{KOR}} <br> {{CAN}}\n| valign=\"top\" |{{FRA}} <br> {{CAN}} <br> {{ITA}} <br> {{USA}} <br> {{AUT}} <br> {{GER}}\n| valign=\"top\" |{{FRA}} <br> {{ITA}} \n|-\n| colspan=5 align=center | <small> If not listed above, one entry is allowed. </small>\n|}\n\n== Schedule ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Discipline\n! Time\n! Segment\n|-\n| rowspan=3|Wednesday, March 18\n| Pairs\n| 10:30\n| Short program\n|-\n| All\n| 14:45\n| Opening ceremony\n|-\n| Ladies\n| 15:45\n| Short program\n|-\n| rowspan=2|Thursday, March 19\n| Men\n| 10:45\n| Short program\n|-\n| Pairs\n| 18:00\n| bgcolor=#f0e68c|Free skating\n|-\n| rowspan=2|Friday, March 20\n| Ice dance\n| 11:25\n| Rhythm dance\n|-\n| Ladies\n| 18:00\n| bgcolor=#f0e68c|Free skating\n|-\n| rowspan=2|Saturday, March 21\n| Ice dance\n| 14:30\n| bgcolor=#f0e68c|Free dance\n|-\n| Men\n| 19:00\n| bgcolor=#f0e68c|Free skating\n|-\n| Sunday, March 22\n| All\n| 16:00\u201318:30\n| ISU Skating Awards\n|-\n| colspan=4 align=center | <small> All times are listed in [[Eastern Time Zone|local time]] (UTC\u221204:00).<ref name=schedule>{{cite web|url=https://montreal2020.com/event-info/event-schedule/|title=Event Schedule \u2013 Montreal 2020|publisher=[[Skate Canada]]|access-date=February 13, 2020}}</ref> </small>\n|}\n\n== Entries ==\nMember nations began announcing their selections in December 2019. The [[International Skating Union]] published a complete list of entries on February 26, 2020.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Country\n! Men<ref name=entries-men>{{cite web|url=http://www.isuresults.com/events/cat03109433.htm|title=ISU World Championships 2020: Men|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n! Ladies<ref name=entries-ladies>{{cite web|url=http://www.isuresults.com/events/cat03109434.htm|title=ISU World Championships 2020: Ladies|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n! Pairs<ref name=entries-pairs>{{cite web|url=http://www.isuresults.com/events/cat03109435.htm|title=ISU World Championships 2020: Pairs|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n! Ice dance<ref name=entries-dance>{{cite web|url=http://www.isuresults.com/events/cat03109436.htm|title=ISU World Championships 2020: Ice Dance|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{ARM}}\n| [[Slavik Hayrapetyan]]\n| [[Anastasia Galustyan]]\n| \n| [[Tina Garabedian]] / [[Simon Proulx-S\u00e9n\u00e9cal]]\n|-\n| {{AUS}}\n| [[Brendan Kerry]]\n| [[Kailani Craine]]\n| \n| [[Holly Harris]] / [[Jason Chan (figure skater)|Jason Chan]]\n|-\n| {{AUT}}\n| [[Maurizio Zandron]]\n| [[Olga Mikutina]]\n| [[Miriam Ziegler]] / [[Severin Kiefer]]\n| \n|-\n| {{AZE}}\n| [[Vladimir Litvintsev]]\n| [[Ekaterina Ryabova (figure skater)|Ekaterina Ryabova]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| {{BLR}}\n| \n| [[Viktoriia Safonova]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| {{BRA}}\n| \n| [[Isadora Williams]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| {{BUL}}\n| [[Larry Loupolover]]\n| [[Alexandra Feigin]]\n| \n| [[Mina Zdravkova]] / [[Christopher M. Davis]]\n|-\n| {{CAN}}<ref name=canada/>\n| [[Nam Nguyen]]\n| [[Emily Bausback]]<br>[[Alicia Pineault]]\n| [[Kirsten Moore-Towers]] / [[Michael Marinaro]]<br>[[Evelyn Walsh]] / [[Trennt Michaud]]\n| [[Piper Gilles]] / [[Paul Poirier]]<br>[[Marjorie Lajoie]] / [[Zachary Lagha]]<br>[[Carolane Soucisse]] / [[Shane Firus]]\n|-\n| {{CHN}}\n| [[Jin Boyang]]\n| [[Chen Hongyi]]\n| [[Peng Cheng]] / [[Jin Yang]]<br>[[Sui Wenjing]] / [[Han Cong]]<br>[[Tang Feiyao]] / [[Yang Yongchao]]\n| [[Wang Shiyue]] / [[Liu Xinyu]]\n|-\n| {{CRO}}\n| \n| \n| [[Lana Petranovi\u0107]] / [[Antonio Souza-Kordeiru]]\n| \n|-\n| {{CZE}}\n| [[Michal B\u0159ezina]]\n| [[Eli\u0161ka B\u0159ezinov\u00e1]]\n| \n| [[Nat\u00e1lie Taschlerov\u00e1]] / [[Filip Taschler]]\n|-\n| {{EST}}\n| [[Aleksandr Selevko]]\n| [[Eva-Lotta Kiibus]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| {{FIN}}<ref name=finland/>\n| \n| [[Emmi Peltonen]]\n| \n| [[Juulia Turkkila]] / [[Matthias Versluis]]\n|-\n| {{FRA}}<ref name=france/>\n| [[K\u00e9vin Aymoz]]\n| [[Ma\u00e9-B\u00e9r\u00e9nice M\u00e9it\u00e9]]\n| [[Cl\u00e9o Hamon]] / [[Denys Strekalin]]<br>[[Coline Keriven]] / [[No\u00ebl-Antoine Pierre]]\n| [[Marie-Jade Lauriault]] / [[Romain Le Gac]]<br>[[Gabriella Papadakis]] / [[Guillaume Cizeron]]\n|-\n| {{GEO}}\n| [[Morisi Kvitelashvili]]\n| [[Alina Urushadze]]\n| \n| [[Maria Kazakova (figure skater)|Maria Kazakova]] / [[Georgy Reviya]]\n|-\n| {{GER}}<ref name=germany/>\n| [[Paul Fentz]]\n| [[Nicole Schott]]\n| [[Minerva Fabienne Hase]] / [[Nolan Seegert]]<br>[[Annika Hocke]] / [[Robert Kunkel]]\n| [[Katharina M\u00fcller]] / [[Tim Dieck]]\n|-\n| {{GBR2}}<ref name=uk/>\n| [[Peter James Hallam]]\n| [[Natasha McKay]]\n| [[Zoe Jones (figure skater)|Zoe Jones]] / [[Christopher Boyadji]]\n| [[Lilah Fear]] / [[Lewis Gibson (figure skater)|Lewis Gibson]]\n|-\n| {{HKG}}\n| \n| [[Yi Christy Leung]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| {{HUN}}\n| \n| [[Ivett T\u00f3th]]\n| [[Ioulia Chtchetinina]] / [[M\u00e1rk Magyar]]\n| [[Emily Monaghan]] / [[Ilias Fourati]]\n|-\n| {{ISR}}\n| [[Alexei Bychenko]]\n| \n| [[Anna Vernikov]] / [[Evgeni Krasnopolski]]\n| [[Shira Ichilov]] / [[Laurent Abecassis]]\n|-\n| {{ITA}}\n| [[Daniel Grassl]]<br>[[Matteo Rizzo]]\n| [[Alessia Tornaghi]]\n| [[Nicole Della Monica]] / [[Matteo Guarise]]<br>[[Rebecca Ghilardi]] / [[Filippo Ambrosini]]\n| [[Charl\u00e8ne Guignard]] / [[Marco Fabbri]]<br>[[Katrine Roy]] / [[Claudio Pietrantonio]]\n|-\n| {{JPN}}<ref name=japan/>\n| [[Yuzuru Hanyu]]<br>[[Keiji Tanaka]]<br>[[Shoma Uno]]\n| [[Wakaba Higuchi]]<br>[[Rika Kihira]]<br>[[Satoko Miyahara]]\n| [[Riku Miura]] / [[Ryuichi Kihara]]\n| [[Misato Komatsubara]] / [[Tim Koleto]]\n|-\n| {{KAZ}}\n| \n| \n| \n| [[Maxine Weatherby]] / [[Temirlan Yerzhanov]]\n|-\n| {{LAT}}\n| [[Deniss Vasi\u013cjevs]]\n| [[Angel\u012bna Ku\u010dva\u013cska]]\n| \n| [[Aurelija Ipolito]] / [[J.T. Michel]]\n|-\n| {{LTU}}\n| \n| \n| \n| [[Allison Reed]] / [[Saulius Ambrulevi\u010dius]]\n|-\n| {{MAS}}\n| [[Julian Yee|Julian Zhi Jie Yee]]\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| {{NED}}<ref name=netherlands/>\n| \n| [[Niki Wories]]\n| [[Daria Danilova]] / [[Michel Tsiba]]\n| \n|-\n| {{PHI}}\n| \n| [[Alisson Perticheto|Alisson Krystle Perticheto]]\n| \n| \n|-\n| {{POL}}\n| \n| [[Ekaterina Kurakova]]\n| \n| [[Natalia Kaliszek]] / [[Maksym Spodyriev]]\n|-\n| {{RUS}}<ref name=russia/>\n| [[Dmitri Aliev]]<br>[[Artur Danielian]]\n| [[Alena Kostornaia]]<br>[[Anna Shcherbakova]]<br>[[Alexandra Trusova]]\n| [[Aleksandra Boikova]] / [[Dmitrii Kozlovskii]]<br>[[Daria Pavliuchenko]] / [[Denis Khodykin]]<br>[[Evgenia Tarasova]] / [[Vladimir Morozov (figure skater)|Vladimir Morozov]]\n| [[Victoria Sinitsina]] / [[Nikita Katsalapov]]<br>[[Alexandra Stepanova]] / [[Ivan Bukin]]<br>[[Tiffany Zahorski]] / [[Jonathan Guerreiro]]\n|-\n| {{KOR}}\n| [[Cha Jun-hwan]]\n| [[Kim Ye-lim (figure skater)|Kim Ye-lim]]<br>[[You Young]]\n| \n| [[Yura Min]] / [[Daniel Eaton (figure skater)|Daniel Eaton]]\n|-\n| {{ESP}}<ref name=spain/>\n| \n| \n| [[Laura Barquero]] / [[T\u00f2n C\u00f3nsul]]\n| [[Olivia Smart]] / [[Adri\u00e1n D\u00edaz]]\n|-\n| {{SWE}}<ref name=sweden/>\n| [[Nikolaj Majorov]]\n| [[Matilda Algotsson]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| {{SUI}}<ref name=switzerland/>\n| [[Lukas Britschgi]]\n| [[Alexia Paganini]]\n|\n| [[Victoria Manni]] / [[Carlo R\u00f6thlisberger]]\n|-\n| {{TUR}}\n| [[Burak Demirbo\u011fa]]\n| \n| \n| [[Nicole Kelly]] / [[Berk Akal\u0131n]]\n|-\n| {{UKR}}<ref name=ukraine/>\n| [[Ivan Shmuratko]]\n| \n| \n| [[Oleksandra Nazarova]] / [[Maxim Nikitin]]\n|-\n| {{USA}}<ref name=usa/>\n| [[Jason Brown (figure skater)|Jason Brown]]<br>[[Nathan Chen]]<br>[[Vincent Zhou]]\n| [[Mariah Bell]]<br>[[Bradie Tennell]]\n| [[Ashley Cain-Gribble]] / [[Timothy LeDuc]]<br>[[Jessica Calalang]] / [[Brian Johnson (figure skater)|Brian Johnson]]\n| [[Madison Chock]] / [[Evan Bates]]<br>[[Kaitlin Hawayek]] / [[Jean-Luc Baker]]<br>[[Madison Hubbell]] / [[Zachary Donohue]]\n|}\n\n=== Changes to preliminary entries ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Discipline\n! Withdrew\n! Added\n! Reason/Other notes\n! Refs\n|-\n| February 26, 2020\n| Pairs\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Alexa Scimeca Knierim]] / [[Chris Knierim]]\n| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jessica Calalang]] / [[Brian Johnson (figure skater)|Brian Johnson]]\n| C. Knierim retired\n| <ref name=usa-pairs>{{cite web | url = https://usfigureskatingfanzone.com/news/2020/2/25/figure-skating-jessica-calalang-and-brian-johnson-added-to-us-world-team.aspx | title = Jessica Calalang and Brian Johnson added to U.S. World Team | publisher = [[U.S. Figure Skating]] | date = February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 5, 2020\n| Ladies\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Anita \u00d6stlund]]\n| {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Matilda Algotsson]]\n| Injury recovery\n| <ref name=ostlund>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9XaLcFpCan/|title=Hi everyone! Unfortunately I have decided to withdraw from the World Championships this year.|first=Anita|last=\u00d6stlund|author-link=Anita \u00d6stlund|type=[[Instagram]]|date=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 6, 2020\n| Ice dance\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Laurence Fournier Beaudry]] / [[Nikolaj S\u00f8rensen]]\n| {{flagicon|CAN}} [[Carolane Soucisse]] / [[Shane Firus]]\n| Recovery\n| <ref name=canada-dance>{{cite tweet|number=1236019242182553603|user=SkateCanada|title=#Montreal2020 announcement: Ice dancers Laurence Fournier Beaudry & Nikolaj Sorensen have withdrawn from the world championships due to Nikolaj recovering from surgery.|author=Skate Canada|author-link=Skate Canada|date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|March 7, 2020\n|Men\n|{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Roman Galay]]\n|N/A\n|\n|\n|-\n|March 9, 2020\n|Men\n|{{flagicon|BLR}} [[Alexander Lebedev (figure skater)|Alexander Lebedev]]\n|N/A\n|\n|\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=announcement>{{cite web|url=https://www.isu.org/docman-documents-links/isu-files/event-documents/figure-skating-4/2019-20/championships-31/announcements-88/22044-world-championships-montreal-2020-announcement/file|title=ISU 2020 World Figure Skating Championships Announcement|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=TES-ladies>{{cite web|url=https://www.isu.org/figure-skating/rules/fsk-communications/23319-isu-communication-2302/file|title=Communication No. 2302: ISU World Figure Skating Championships 2020, Minimum Total Elements Score - Ladies|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]|date=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=host>{{cite press release|url=https://skatecanada.ca/2017/09/13723/|title=Skate Canada to host the ISU World Figure Skating Championships\u00ae 2020 in Montreal|date=September 21, 2017|publisher=[[Skate Canada]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=n_entries>{{cite web|url=https://www.isu.org/inside-isu/isu-communications/communications/21554-isu-communication-2266/file|title=Entries for ISU Figure Skating and Synchronized Skating Championships 2020|publisher=[[International Skating Union]]}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=canada>\n* {{cite press release|url=https://skatecanada.ca/2020/01/skate-canada-names-teams-for-2020-isu-championships/|title=Skate Canada names teams for 2020 ISU Championships|publisher=[[S