{"title_page": "1975\u201376 DDR-Oberliga", "text_new": "{{Other|1975\u201376 Oberliga (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox football league season\n| competition        = [[DDR-Oberliga]]\n| logo               = \n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| season             = 1975\u201376\n| winners            = [[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| promoted           = \n| relegated          = {{ubl|[[FC Sachsen Leipzig|BSG Chemie Leipzig]]|[[FC Energie Cottbus|BSG Energie Cottbus]]}}\n| continentalcup1    = [[1976\u201377 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = Dynamo Dresden\n| continentalcup2    = [[1976\u201377 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n| continentalcup3    = [[1976\u201377 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = {{ubl|[[Berliner FC Dynamo]]|[[1. FC Magdeburg]]}}\n| matches            = 182\n| total goals        = 575\n| league topscorer   = [[Hans-J\u00fcrgen Kreische]] (24)<ref>''fuwo'', page: 93</ref>\n| attendance         = 2,283,200<ref name=\"Fuwo\" >''fuwo'', page: 23</ref>\n| average attendance = 12,545<ref name=\"Fuwo\" />\n| prevseason = [[1974\u201375 DDR-Oberliga|1974\u201375]]\n| nextseason = [[1976\u201377 DDR-Oberliga|1976\u201377]]\n}}\nThe '''1975\u201376 DDR-Oberliga''' was the 27th season of the [[DDR-Oberliga]], the first tier of [[East German football league system|league football]] in [[East Germany]].\n\nThe league was contested by fourteen teams. [[Dynamo Dresden]] won the championship, the club's fourth of eight East German championships. The 1975\u201376 championship marked the beginning of a new era in the Oberliga with fifteen consecutive league titles between 1975 and 1990 going to the ''Dynamo'' clubs, Dynamo Dresden and [[Berliner FC Dynamo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrchamp.html |title= East Germany - List of Champions |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref name=\"Meister\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/meister/ |title= DDR-Meister |date= |website=dfb.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title= East German champions}}</ref>\n\n[[Hans-J\u00fcrgen Kreische]] of Dynamo Dresden was the league's top scorer with 24 goals, the record fourth time for Kreische to finish as league top scorer,<ref name=\"Goal\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/torschuetzenkoenige/gdr-oberliga/ |title= DDDR \u00bb Oberliga \u00bb Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige  |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 25 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga top scorers }}</ref> while [[J\u00fcrgen Croy]] of [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]] won the seasons [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|East German Footballer of the year]] award.<ref>''fuwo'', page: 92</ref>\n\nOn the strength of the 1975\u201376 title Dresden qualified for the [[1976\u201377 European Cup]] where the club was knocked out by [[FC Z\u00fcrich]] in the quarter finals. Fourth-placed club [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]] qualified for the [[1976\u201377 European Cup Winners' Cup]] as the seasons [[FDGB-Pokal]] winners and was knocked out by [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] in the first round. Second-placed [[Berliner FC Dynamo]] qualified for the [[1976\u201377 UEFA Cup]] where it was knocked out in the first round by [[Shakhtar Donetsk]] while third-placed [[1. FC Magdeburg]] lost to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197677.html |title= European Competitions 1976-77 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nThe 1975\u201376 season saw two newly promoted clubs [[FC Sachsen Leipzig|BSG Chemie Leipzig]] and [[FC Energie Cottbus|BSG Energie Cottbus]].<ref name=\"Ddr\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrhist.html |title= East Germany 1946-1990 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spielplan/gdr-oberliga-1975-1976-spieltag/26/ |title= DDR-Oberliga 1975\u201376 |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=}}</ref>\n{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|res_col_header=QR\n|sortable_table=y\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=DRE|name_DRE=[[Dynamo Dresden]]\n|team2=DYN|name_DYN=[[BFC Dynamo]]\n|team3=FCM|name_FCM=[[1. FC Magdeburg]]\n|team4=LEI|name_LEI=[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n|team5=CZJ|name_CZJ=[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena]]\n|team6=AUE|name_AUE=[[FC Erzgebirge Aue|BSG Wismut Aue]]\n|team7=RWE|name_RWE=[[FC Rot-Weiss Erfurt]]\n|team8=CHE|name_CHE=[[Hallescher FC|Hallescher FC Chemie]]\n|team9=ZWI|name_ZWI=[[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]]\n|team10=RIE|name_RIE=[[Stahl Riesa]]\n|team11=KMS|name_KMS=[[Chemnitzer FC|FC Karl-Marx-Stadt]]\n|team12=VOR|name_VOR=[[FC Vorw\u00e4rts Frankfurt]]\n|team13=CHM|name_CHM=[[FC Sachsen Leipzig|BSG Chemie Leipzig]]\n|team14=COT|name_COT=[[FC Energie Cottbus|BSG Energie Cottbus]]\n|win_DRE=19|draw_DRE=5|loss_DRE=2|gf_DRE=70|ga_DRE=23\n|win_DYN=17|draw_DYN=3|loss_DYN=6|gf_DYN=67|ga_DYN=24\n|win_FCM=15|draw_FCM=6|loss_FCM=5|gf_FCM=59|ga_FCM=33\n|win_LEI=13|draw_LEI=5|loss_LEI=8|gf_LEI=40|ga_LEI=34\n|win_CZJ=11|draw_CZJ=7|loss_CZJ=8|gf_CZJ=50|ga_CZJ=43\n|win_AUE=9|draw_AUE=9|loss_AUE=8|gf_AUE=30|ga_AUE=35\n|win_RWE=8|draw_RWE=10|loss_RWE=8|gf_RWE=44|ga_RWE=36\n|win_CHE=9|draw_CHE=7|loss_CHE=10|gf_CHE=37|ga_CHE=35\n|win_ZWI=7|draw_ZWI=8|loss_ZWI=11|gf_ZWI=29|ga_ZWI=43\n|win_RIE=7|draw_RIE=7|loss_RIE=12|gf_RIE=35|ga_RIE=46\n|win_KMS=7|draw_KMS=7|loss_KMS=12|gf_KMS=25|ga_KMS=41\n|win_VOR=8|draw_VOR=4|loss_VOR=14|gf_VOR=41|ga_VOR=57\n|win_CHM=4|draw_CHM=6|loss_CHM=16|gf_CHM=25|ga_CHM=62\n|win_COT=3|draw_COT=6|loss_COT=17|gf_COT=23|ga_COT=63\n\n|col_EC=green1|text_EC=League champion and qualified for the [[European Cup]]\n|result1=EC\n|col_UC=blue1|text_UC=Qualified for the [[UEFA Cup]]\n|result2=UC|result3=UC\n|col_CWC=yellow1|text_CWC=[[FDGB-Pokal]] winner and qualified for the [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n|result4=CWC\n|col_R=red1|text_R=[[Promotion and relegation|Relegated]] to [[DDR-Liga]]\n|result13=R|result14=R\n|update=complete|source=\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{cite magazine |last= |first= |date=1991 |title= Das war unser Fu\u00dfball im Osten|trans-title= This was our football in the East|language=German |magazine= Fu\u00dfball-Woche (fuwo)|location=Berlin |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE|Axel-Springer-Verlag]]}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.f-archiv.de/ Das Deutsche Fussball Archiv] {{in lang|de}} Historic German league tables\n\n{{DDR-Oberliga seasons}}\n{{1975\u201376 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ddr-Oberliga 1975-76}}\n[[Category:1975\u201376 in German football leagues]]\n[[Category:1975\u201376 in East German football|1]]\n[[Category:DDR-Oberliga seasons|1975-76]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other|1975\u201376 Oberliga (disambiguation)}}\n{{infobox football league season\n| competition                = [[DDR-Oberliga]]\n| logo                       =\n| image                      =\n| pixels                     = \n| caption                  = \n| season                     = 1975\u201376\n| winners                    = [[Dynamo Dresden]]\n| promoted                   = \n| relegated                  = [[FC Sachsen Leipzig|BSG Chemie Leipzig]]{{-}}[[FC Energie Cottbus|BSG Energie Cottbus]]\n| continentalcup1            = [[1976\u201377 European Cup|European Cup]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = Dynamo Dresden\n| continentalcup2           = [[1976\u201377 European Cup Winners' Cup|European Cup Winners' Cup]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers =[[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]]\n| continentalcup3                = [[1976\u201377 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers =[[Berliner FC Dynamo]]{{-}}[[1. FC Magdeburg]]\n| matches                       = 182\n| total goals                     = 575\n| league topscorer           = [[Hans-J\u00fcrgen Kreische]] (24)<ref>''fuwo'', page: 93</ref>\n| attendance                    = 2,283,200<ref name=\"Fuwo\" >''fuwo'', page: 23</ref>\n| average attendance      = 12,545<ref name=\"Fuwo\" />\n| prevseason                 = [[1974\u201375 DDR-Oberliga|1974\u201375]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1976\u201377 DDR-Oberliga|1976\u201377]]\n}}\nThe '''1975\u201376 DDR-Oberliga''' was the 27th season of the [[DDR-Oberliga]], the first tier of [[East German football league system|league football]] in [[East Germany]].\n\nThe league was contested by fourteen teams. [[Dynamo Dresden]] won the championship, the club's fourth of eight East German championships. The 1975\u201376 championship marked the beginning of a new era in the Oberliga with fifteen consecutive league titles between 1975 and 1990 going to the ''Dynamo'' clubs, Dynamo Dresden and [[Berliner FC Dynamo]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrchamp.html |title= East Germany - List of Champions |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref name=\"Meister\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/meister/ |title= DDR-Meister |date= |website=dfb.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title= East German champions}}</ref>\n\n[[Hans-J\u00fcrgen Kreische]] of Dynamo Dresden was the league's top scorer with 24 goals, the record fourth time for Kreische to finish as league top scorer,<ref name=\"Goal\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/torschuetzenkoenige/gdr-oberliga/ |title= DDDR \u00bb Oberliga \u00bb Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige  |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 25 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga top scorers }}</ref> while [[J\u00fcrgen Croy]] of [[FSV Zwickau|BSG Sachsenring Zwickau]] won the seasons [[Footballer of the Year in Germany|East German Footballer of the year]] award.<ref>''fuwo'', page: 92</ref>\n\nOn the strength of the 1975\u201376 title Dresden qualified for the [[1976\u201377 European Cup]] where the club was knocked out by [[FC Z\u00fcrich]] in the quarter finals. Fourth-placed club [[1. FC Lokomotive Leipzig]] qualified for the [[1976\u201377 European Cup Winners' Cup]] as the seasons [[FDGB-Pokal]] winners and was knocked out by [[Heart of Midlothian F.C.|Heart of Midlothian]] in the first round. Second-placed [[Berliner FC Dynamo]] qualified for the [[1976\u201377 UEFA Cup]] where it was knocked out in the first round by [[Shakhtar Donetsk]] while third-placed [[1. FC Magdeburg]] lost to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the quarter finals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec197677.html |title= European Competitions 1976-77 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nThe 1975\u201376 season saw two newly promoted clubs [[FC Sachsen Leipzig|BSG Chemie Leipzig]] and [[FC Energie Cottbus|BSG Energie Cottbus]].<ref name=\"Ddr\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrhist.html |title= East Germany 1946-1990 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spielplan/gdr-oberliga-1975-1976-spieltag/26/ |title= DDR-Oberliga 1975\u201376 |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 26 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=}}</ref>\n{{fb cl header|sort=y|winpoints=2}}\n|-style=\"background:#ddffdd\"\n||1||[[Dynamo Dresden]]||26||19||5||2||70||23||+47||43\n|-style=\"background:#fffacd\"\n||2||[[BFC Dynamo]]||26||17||3||6||67||24||+43||37\n|-style=\"background:#fffacd\"\n||3||[[1. FC Magdeburg]]||26||15||6||5||59||33||+26||36\n|-style=\"background:#E6E